Before learning any framework, it is very important to understand why that framework was created. It is also important to understand that Quarkus is not the first Java framework. Before Quarkus, there were many Java frameworks. So the question is:

What is so new and special in Quarkus that makes it different from other frameworks?
   Let’s first goto the official Quarkus website https://quarkus.io/
We can see Quarkus has emphasized these two points, the first one is Supersonic and the second one is Super Atomic
    First, let’s understand what Supersonic means.It means that the execution speed of Quarkus applications is very fast, because Quarkus only compiles the classes that are actually needed and ignores the unnecessary ones. 
   Now let’s understand Super Atomic. We know that an atom is very small, so Super Atomic means the final application size is very small compared to other frameworks. Since the size is small and fewer classes are loaded, the execution speed becomes faster and the application loads very quickly.
   So, Quarkus provides us with two major advantages. So whenever we build any software, we mainly focus on two things:
1. Time
2. Memory

So Quarkus projects consume less memory and have a faster startup time. Because of these two advantages, we get a very smooth live reloading experience in Quarkus projects compared to Spring Boot.

What live reloading ?
     Suppose we are developing a Quarkus project and also a Spring Boot project. We run both applications and they start producing output.
Now, if we make any change in a file in the Quarkus project, that change is immediately reflected in the output, without recompiling the project and without stopping and restarting the application. The changes are reflected live. Whereas in the case of Spring Boot, we usually need to restart the application to see the changes or we have to add dev tool dependency 
    You will notice that the live reloading speed in Quarkus is so fast that we won’t even realize your project has been recompiled and reloaded.
Whereas in the case of Spring Boot, we usually have to wait for some time before the changes are reflected. Because of this live reloading feature, during the project development phase, we get a very smooth development experience, because Quarkus compiles only the required class files, resulting in fewer compiled classes.

Both Spring Boot and Quarkus are excellent frameworks in their own ways. However, since Quarkus was introduced after Spring Boot, it naturally comes with new and improved features

