    But whenever we call our own Quarkus API from the frontend. Suppose our frontend is built using Angular. When Angular (or any frontend application) tries to call our Quarkus API, we may see a CORS error in the browser.
     It means, we are trying to access resources from another server
But we don’t have permission to do so. So when one server tries to access another server’s APIs, the target server must explicitly allow it.

quarkus.http.cors=true
quarkus.http.cors.origin=*
quarkus.http.cors.methods=GET,POST


Microprofile fault tolerance with Quarkus
       Suppose in our project, we are calling someone else’s API on another project. But due to some reason, the server is down, or they changed their API path. In that case we get 404 – Page Not Found, because that API no longer exists. So that error will be visible to our application and to our end user.
       So we create a method with @FallbackMethod, so if any error occurs—whether the API path changes or the server does not respond—then immediately the fallback method will be executed and return any message, such as
“Site is under maintenance” or any custom message we want
       The fallback method’s signature must be exactly the same as the original method.

1. We need to add extension called "quarkus-smallrye-fault-tolerance"
