Fault Tolerance Annotations
1. @Fallback
2. @Retry(maxRetries = 3)
         When method calls some other API. If the first call fails, it retries again and if it fails again, it retries again. It will retry 3 times.
If after 3 retries there is still no response, then if a fallback method is defined fallback is executed, otherwise error is returned
        So with @Retry, the application does not give up immediately.

3. @Timeout.
       Suppose API takes 10–12 seconds to respond. During this time, the user keeps seeing “Loading…”, and thinks “Something is wrong, the app is not working.” To avoid this, we define a timeout.

@Timeout(2000)

This means we wait 2 seconds, if no response comes within 2 seconds → execution stops and then fallback logic is triggered

Retry + Timeout Together
If you use both Retry and Timeout, then:
- First, the system waits for the timeout duration
- If no response arrives, it retries
- This process repeats for the retry count
- If it still fails → fallback method executes


4. @CircuitBreaker
       Suppose we built a Cricket Score App. This app shows live cricket scores. We do not have our own data, so we call Cricbuzz API. Now imagine
Cricbuzz API goes down, our app keeps calling it continuously
Retry → fallback → retry → fallback → retry…
      This creates unnecessary load on our application. We already know the service is down, so why keep hitting it repeatedly?

When a dependent service keeps failing:
- We break the circuit
- Stop calling the service for some time
- After a delay, we try again
This prevents unnecessary load.

@CircuitBreaker(
    requestVolumeThreshold = 4,
    failureRatio = 0.5,
    delay = 10s
)

Suppose we make the first call and we do not get any response. At this point, this annotation does not do anything special; the execution simply continues. 
Then we call again—still no response. We call again—still no response.
We call again—still no response. So we have called it four times, and we have not received any response at all.
    So we called it four times and How many times did we get a response? Zero times. So what is the probability of getting a response? Zero, right?
    Now let’s understand another case. You call it once—no response.
You call it again—no response. You call it again—no response. You call it a fourth time—and this time you do get a response.
   So out of four calls, you got one successful response. What is the probability now? 0.25 (25%)
   Now suppose our failure threshold is 0.5. If the success ratio is less than 0.5, then:
- In the first case, it was 0
- In the second case, it was 0.25
Both are below 0.5.

So in this situation, what will happen? We will NOT send the next (fifth) request. Instead, we will wait for 10 seconds.

How Request Volume Threshold Works
     You define a value in requestVolumeThreshold. Before sending any new request, the system checks:
    What was the status of the previous four requests?

If the success ratio of those four requests is below the defined threshold, then the circuit remains open means stop sending requests

