Exception Handling using ExceptionMapper
     In our project, mainly we face two types of exceptions:
1. Technical Exceptions
2. Business Exceptions

1. Technical Exceptions
As the name suggests, technical exceptions occur due to technical issues, such as NullPointerException, Database exceptions, SQL errors, Wrong queries, Configuration issues

2. Business Exceptions
Business exceptions are project- or domain-specific. Suppose you are building a banking application. When adding a new user, name is mandatory, PAN card is mandatory
These are business-related rules, so such exceptions are called Business Exceptions.

To handle exceptions properly in Quarkus, we mainly do three things.

Step 1: Create an Error Message Class
   So whenever an exception occurs we return a Response object. So inside the response entity, instead of returning the actual exception, we return this ErrorMessage object. So the client (Postman, frontend, mobile app) will not see the actual exception, instead they will see a clean error response

Step 2: Create Custom Exception Classes

Step 3: Create ExceptionMapper class which used to catch any custom exception that is thrown
and return a Response object, inside the response, it returns an ErrorMessage object


