Quarkus Application Initialization and Termination 
    When your Quarkus application starts, if at that time you want to execute some business logic,
initialize some resources, start some threads. And when your application ends at that time you want to execute some code, free all the resources and stop all the running threads

1. @QuarkusMain
      You can apply it on any class, inside this class, you write a normal Java main method.
Now this class becomes the main class and when you execute this class all logic inside it runs
and after that, the Quarkus project starts automatically. You don’t need to write Maven commands manually. Just run this class, and the entire project starts.
      You should not write all your business logic directly inside this class, because that code may execute before Quarkus is fully started

@QuarkusMain
public class MyMainClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
       Quarkus.run(args);
    }
}

As soon as you apply @QuarkusMain, this becomes the main class for Quarkus. Just like Java has only one main method, Quarkus also allows only one @QuarkusMain class. If you apply it on two classes, you will get an error.

2. @Startup
      When you apply this annotation on a class the methods inside that class can be executed during application startup by using @PostConstruct(Database initialization
Creating connections) and @PreDestroy

For example as soon as the application starts we need to initialize resources and start background tasks

3. @Observes StartupEvent
      when your application is fully started, when all the resources in your project are fully initialized, only then this method will be executed. At this stage, you write the logic which is not initialization logic, but your actual business logic and your main functionality

4. @Observes ShutdownEvent
       The appl has not stopped yet, but it is about to stop, at that time, the Shutdown Event comes. After that, when you finally stop the appl, then @PreDestroy is executed.

When you execute the class:
- First, startup-related annotations come into action
- Initialization logic runs
- When the application is fully initialized, the Startup Event is fired
- When all work is done and the application is about to stop, the Shutdown Event is fired
- After that, the application is destroyed in @PreDestroy

1. Refer Quarkus1 project, Create java main class

- This is a normal Java main class. If we run it normally, it will run like a Java program.
But in Quarkus’ eyes, this is still not a main class. To make it a main class in Quarkus, we use 
@QuarkusMain

@QuarkusMain
public class Main {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		

	}
}

- Now if we execute this class, only the code inside the main method will execute. After that, the project will stop. So Quarkus will not start fully, to start the Quarkus application, we must write

@QuarkusMain
public class Main {
	public static void main(String[] args) {		
         Quarkus.run(args);
	}
}

Now if you only write logic inside the main method, it will execute and then the application will stop. But we want logic to execute and the application to keep running continuously. 

- So for that, we create another class which implements QuarkusApplication interface and pass it as an argument and override run()

@QuarkusMain
public class Main {
	public static void main(String[] args) {		
         Quarkus.run(MainQuarkus.class,args);
	}
	public static class MainQuarkus implements QuarkusApplication {

		@Override
		public int run(String... args) throws Exception {
			System.out.println(">>>>> Application is starting....");
            Quarkus.waitForExit();
            return 0;
		}
		
	}
}

So when we run the main class, the message prints, the application start and the server runs

