MicroProfile Health with Quarkus
     Whenever we build a Quarkus application, we connect it to a database, and inside the application we also call some external pages or APIs. So you can understand that our application is never completely independent. We connect it to a database or external servers or external APIs.
Suppose if any one of these goes down then our application breaks, because it depends on external resources.
    Now we go into the error logs, debug the issue, and finally realize that the database is down 
or the external API we are calling is down or the API path has changed. To avoid this situation, we use MicroProfile Health.

Why MicroProfile Health?
     In Microprofile we monitor all the external resources that affect our application’s health.
For example we monitor whether the database is live and ready and we monitor whether the external API is up and running
    So when our project goes down for any reason, the first thing we check whether any of the external resources down?. If something is down, we can immediately identify it and fix it.
But if we don’t know what is down, we waste a lot of time debugging. That’s why this is a very important feature.

First, we need to add a dependency called SmallRye-Health  to our project.Once we add this dependency, it gives us two important annotations:
1. @Liveness
This tells us whether the application (or external API) is alive
Meaning: if we call it now, will it respond or not?

2. @Readiness
This tells us whether the application is ready to serve requests
Meaning: are all required resources (database, APIs) initialized and ready?

