JWT VERIFY → Check the token (using a public/secret key) and verification happens on every request.

JWT verification is checking:
- Is the signature valid?
- Was the token issued by a trusted issuer?
- Is it expired?
- Is it intended for this service?

JWT SIGN → Create the token (using a private/secret key), Signing happens once (when user logs in).

JWT signing is the act of:
- Taking header + payload
- Applying a cryptographic algorithm
- Using a secret or private key
- Producing a signature

This signature proves who created the token and that it was not modified

16. Create AuthResource class to authenticate a user and issue a JWT token.

@Path("/api/auth")
@Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
@Consumes(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
public class AuthResource {

    //input from client
    public record LoginRequest(String username, String password) {}
    //output to client
    public record TokenResponse(String token) {}

    @Inject UserService userService;
    @Inject PasswordService passwordService;

    @POST
    @Path("/login")
    @PermitAll
    public TokenResponse login(LoginRequest req) {

        if (req.username() == null || req.password() == null) {
            throw new BadRequestException("username/password required");
        }

        User user = userService.findByUsername(req.username())
                .orElseThrow(() -> new NotAuthorizedException("Invalid credentials"));

        if (!user.active) {
            throw new ForbiddenException("User is inactive");
        }

        // ✅ BCrypt verify
        if (!passwordService.matches(req.password(), user.passwordHash)) {
            throw new NotAuthorizedException("Invalid credentials");
        }

        // ✅ JWT issue with role from DB
        String token = Jwt.issuer("book-api")  //Identifies who issued the token
                .upn(user.username)  //Sets the authenticated principal
                .groups(Set.of(user.role))  //Roles for RBAC
                .expiresAt(Instant.now().plus(Duration.ofHours(1)))  //token expiration
                .sign();   //Cryptographically signs JWT

        return new TokenResponse(token);
    }
}


