Complex JOINs in Quarkus Reactive MySQL
Example schema (realistic)
movies(id, title, category_id)
categories(id, name)
reviews(id, movie_id, rating)
users(id, name)

Simple Inner Join

public static Uni<List<MovieView>> findMoviesWithCategory(MySQLPool client) {
    return client
        .query("""
            SELECT m.id, m.title, c.name AS category
            FROM movies m
            JOIN categories c ON m.category_id = c.id
        """)
        .execute()
        .onItem()
        .transform(rows -> {
            List<MovieView> list = new ArrayList<>();
            for (Row r : rows) {
                list.add(new MovieView(
                    r.getLong("id"),
                    r.getString("title"),
                    r.getString("category")
                ));
            }
            return list;
        });
}

✅ JOIN logic is pure SQL
✅ Mapping is explicit and safe
✅ Works exactly as described in the Quarkus Reactive SQL Client guide [quarkus.io]


Left Join
Use case: Movies may not have reviews, but we still want them.

public static Uni<List<MovieRatingView>> findMoviesWithRatings(MySQLPool client) {
    return client
        .query("""
            SELECT m.id, m.title, r.rating
            FROM movies m
            LEFT JOIN reviews r ON m.id = r.movie_id
        """)
        .execute()
        .onItem()
        .transform(rows -> {
            List<MovieRatingView> list = new ArrayList<>();
            for (Row r : rows) {
                list.add(new MovieRatingView(
                    r.getLong("id"),
                    r.getString("title"),
                    r.getInteger("rating") // may be null
                ));
            }
            return list;
        });
}

Multi‑table JOIN with aggregation (GROUP BY)
Use case: Movie + category + average rating

public static Uni<List<MovieStats>> findMovieStats(MySQLPool client) {
    return client
        .query("""
            SELECT m.id, m.title, c.name AS category,
                   AVG(r.rating) AS avg_rating
            FROM movies m
            JOIN categories c ON m.category_id = c.id
            LEFT JOIN reviews r ON r.movie_id = m.id
            GROUP BY m.id, m.title, c.name
        """)
        .execute()
        .onItem()
        .transform(rows -> {
            List<MovieStats> list = new ArrayList<>();
            for (Row r : rows) {
                list.add(new MovieStats(
                    r.getLong("id"),
                    r.getString("title"),
                    r.getString("category"),
                    r.getDouble("avg_rating")
                ));
            }
            return list;
        });
}

JOIN with parameters (WHERE on joined table)

public static Uni<List<MovieReviewerView>> findByReviewer(
    MySQLPool client, Long userId
) {
    return client
        .preparedQuery("""
            SELECT m.id, m.title, u.name AS reviewer
            FROM movies m
            JOIN reviews r ON m.id = r.movie_id
            JOIN users u ON r.user_id = u.id
            WHERE u.id = ?
        """)
        .execute(Tuple.of(userId))
        .onItem()
        .transform(rows -> {
            List<MovieReviewerView> list = new ArrayList<>();
            for (Row r : rows) {
                list.add(new MovieReviewerView(
                    r.getLong("id"),
                    r.getString("title"),
                    r.getString("reviewer")
                ));
            }
            return list;
        });
}


JOIN + pagination (real‑world pattern)

public static Uni<List<MovieView>> findPaged(
    MySQLPool client, int limit, int offset
) {
    return client
        .preparedQuery("""
            SELECT m.id, m.title, c.name AS category
            FROM movies m
            JOIN categories c ON m.category_id = c.id
            ORDER BY m.title
            LIMIT ? OFFSET ?
        """)
        .execute(Tuple.of(limit, offset))
        .onItem()
        .transform(rows -> {
            List<MovieView> list = new ArrayList<>();
            for (Row r : rows) list.add(MovieView.from(r));
            return list;
        });
}

Java bean mappings with MapStruct and Quarkus
    A DTO(Data Transfer Object) is used to transfer data between different layers or modules of an application, such as:
 - Between the REST layer and the service layer
 - Between the service layer and the client
 - Between different microservices
A DTO:
- Is a simple Java class
- Contains only fields and getters/setters
- Has no business logic
- Is used only for input and output

What is a DAO (Data Access Object)?
     A DAO(Data Access Object) is responsible for interacting with the data storage layer, performing CRUD operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete) and isolating database logic from business logic

Why use DTOs and DAOs together?
Using DTOs and DAOs helps to:
- Keep a clean architecture
- Avoid exposing database entities directly
- Make applications easier to maintain and extend
- Improve security and flexibility


What is MapStruct?
    MapStruct is a Java annotation processor that automatically generates mapping code. Instead of writing manual mapping logic like this:

dto.setTitle(entity.getTitle());
dto.setDescription(entity.getDescription());

